1. Create a Repository on GitHub
2. Fork a Repository
3. Clone the Forked Repository Locally

bash
git clone <forked-repository-url>


4. Create a New Branch for Your Changes
bash
git checkout -b feature/my-changes

5. Make Changes and Commit
 . Make your changes in the code.
 . Stage and commit your changes:
   bash
   git add .
   git commit -m "Describe your changes"
   
6. Push Changes to Your Fork
bash
git remote add origin <forked-repo>
git push origin feature/my-changes

7. Create a Pull Request

1. Go to your forked repository on GitHub.
2. You will see a prompt to create a pull request. Click on *Compare & pull request*.
3. Fill in the pull request details (title, description) and click *Create pull request*.

8. Merge the Pull Request

1. Once the pull request is created, you (or the repository owner) can review the changes.
2. If everything looks good, click the *Merge pull request* button.
3. Confirm the merge.

